[normal]Draft Deregulation Bill[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Consultation submission on Clause 25
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25 Removal of duty to order re-hearing of marine accident investigations
[normal]In section 269(1) of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 (power to order re-hearing
[normal]of
[normal] investigation into marine accident and duty to do so in certain cases).
[normal](a) 
[normal]omit
[normal] paragraph (a) (duty to order re-hearing where new and important
[normal]evidence
[normal] discovered), and the .or. 
[normal]following
[normal] it;
[normal](b) 
[normal]in
[normal] paragraph (b), omit .other..
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]269[bold]Re-hearing of and appeal from investigations.[bold](1) Where a formal investigation has been held under section 268 the Secretary of State may order the whole or part of the case to be re-heard, and shall do so—
[normal](a) 
[normal]if
[normal] new and important evidence which could not be produced at the investigation has been discovered; or
[normal](b) 
[normal]if
[normal] there appear to the Secretary of State to be 
[normal]other
[normal] grounds for suspecting that a miscarriage of justice may have occurred.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]UKMPA Comment:[bold]The UKMPA is concerned as to the intended meaning of “a miscarriage of Justice”.  
